Your Honor,

I stand before you today as a defendant who takes full responsibility for my actions. I plead guilty to the offense of speeding, as I drove my brand-new car without regard for the safety of those around me. I recognize the danger I posed and I deeply regret my reckless behavior.

I must admit that I was caught up in the thrill of experiencing the speed of my new car, and this clouded my judgment. However, I understand that my actions were inexcusable, and I acknowledge the seriousness of the offense.

Although I did not initially respond to the Notice of Intended Prosecution (NIP), it was not out of a deliberate intent to evade the consequences of my actions. It was due to my negligence in handling my mail. If I had seen the notice, I would have taken immediate action to rectify my mistake. I acknowledge this as a significant factor in my guilt.

I acknowledge that I am a young individual, at the age of 26, and it is unfortunate that I already have penalty points on my license from previous speeding incidents. However, I would like to emphasize that other than these driving offenses, I have had no record of criminal behavior.

It is important to note that I have been diagnosed with ADHD, which can sometimes impair my ability to fully focus on tasks and make sound decisions. I do not offer this as an excuse for my actions, but rather as a mitigating factor that may have influenced my judgment on that particular day.

I would like to assure the court that I have already taken steps to make amends for the harm I have caused by attending a defensive driving course. This course has provided me with valuable knowledge and skills to prevent similar offenses from occurring in the future. I have also proactively sought therapy and implemented strategies to better manage my ADHD, demonstrating my commitment to personal growth and self-improvement.

Lastly, I want to express the genuine remorse I feel for the danger I created and the inconveniences I caused. I understand the gravity of my actions and the potential consequences they could have had. I am committed to learning from this experience and becoming a law-abiding citizen who contributes positively to society.

In conclusion, Your Honor, I admit my guilt and take full responsibility for my actions. I sincerely regret my recklessness and the potential harm I caused. I humbly ask for your leniency and understanding as I strive to learn from this mistake and work towards becoming a responsible member of society. Thank you for your attention.

